Estimating R0 from a simple epidemic

For free-living organisms, the rate of exponential growth r given generation time G can be calculated as follows \[r = log(R_0) / G\] \[R_0 = exp(rG)\]

Since an exponentially growing population grows as a rate \[N(t) = N(0)exp(rt)\] the time for it to double will be \[log(2)/r\]

For pathogens, N would represent disease prevalence and G the serial interval V, the time between successive cases in a chain of transmission. Since infectious disease data often is in the form of incidence (i), to calculate R_0 we can first regress log (cumulative incidence) on time to estimate the rate of exponential increase r. \[r = log(cumulative_i)\\R_0 = Vr + 1\]

Example: 2003 Niamey measles outbreak

We can first visusally inspect the data (niamey available in the package epidemr) to identify the initial period of exponential growth. Note the time series is provided in weeks, so we will need to use this as our basic time unit for subsequent calculations.

The serial interval for measles is of 10-12 days. Since data is weekly in this example, we can assume V of 1.5 or 1.8 and use the equations for a quick calculation for R_0, which places its value at between 1.7 and 1.8. \[r = log(cumulative_i)\\R_0 = Vr + 1\]

# Regressing cumulative incidence in time 
fit=lm(log(cum_cases)~absweek, subset=absweek<7, data=niamey)

r=fit$coef["absweek"]
V=c(1.5, 1.8)
V*r+1
## [1] 1.694233 1.833080
Effective reproductive number

Our estimation of R_0 for the Niamey measles outbreak really represents R_E, the effective reproductive number. That is, the reproductive number at the start of the outbreak in a population with a background level of immunity against measles due to vaccination. Intuitively then, R_E should be higher than our estimate above.

We can thus refine our estimate of R by acounting for the ratio of infectious period to serial interval (f). For measles, the infectious period is 5 days, or in our example 5/7 to put it in the same time scale. We can then use the following equation to solve for R \[R = Vr + 1 + f(1-f)(Vr)^2\]

f = (5/7)/V
V * r + 1 + f * (1 - f) * (V * r)^2
## [1] 1.814450 1.999198

This estimation of R_E places its value at between 1.8 and 2.0. Whilst its simplicity makes it very useful at the start of an outbreak, its based on initial growth only. For a full or evolving outbreak, though, such simple calculations are not very robust, as they rely on a fraction of the data.

Maximum likelihood: the chain-binomial model

In contrast to the continuous-time, deterministic, basic-chain SIR model from chapter 2, the chain-binomial model assumes that an epidemic arises from a succession of discrete generations of infectious individuals in a coin-flip fashion given a force of infection () \[\beta\ I/N\]

The negative of the above expression will thus be the probability that a susceptible individual escapes infection at time t. The number of events in t will follow a Poisson distribution (xt). Assuming that a) contacts happen at random and b) the serial interval is the basic unit of time t, the stochastic chain-binomial model can be represented as follows \[I_{t+1} \sim Binomial(S_t, 1 - exp(-\beta\ I_t / N)\\S_{t+1} = S_t - I_{t+1} = S_0 - \sum_{i=1}^t I_i\]

If we ignore observational error, there are two unknown parameters in these expressions: the initial number of susceptibles (S_0) and the transmission rate. The reproductive ratio is a composite of these two \[R = S_0(1exp(\beta /N))\]

For a large population, the reproductive ratio is approximately S0/N because 1exp(x) ~ x for x << 1. Thus is approximately the reproductive ratio at the beginning of the epidemic, since infectious individuals are expected to transmit for exactly a time unit before recovering.

The removal method for parameter estimation in a chain-binomial model

Assuming conditional independence (i.e.each epidemic generation depends only on the state of the system in the previous time step), the removal method can estimate and S_0 from a sequence of binomial likelihoods. In contrast to the examples above with the Niamey measles outbreak, the removal method uses all available data and not just a few time points at the start of an outbreak.

We will implement the removal method by doing a non-standard maximum-likelihood analysis:

  1. We write a function (model) for the likelihood (L)
  2. Our model needs to be parameterised by candidate values for S_0 and
  3. Our data will be an actual case series of infected individuals I
  4. Assuming a fully susceptible population at the start of the outbreak, S_0 needs to be at least the number of actual cases in an epidemic
  5. Our model can then be used to obtain the negative log-likelihood of observing the data given the model. In this example, the base R function dbinom is uses for this purpose

In this example, we will again use data from the Niamey measles outbreak for district_1. The outbreak lasted 31 weeks and there were a total of 5,920 cases in district 1. So we will use candidate values of 6,500 for S_0 and a sequence of potential candidate values for going from 0 to 10 by 0.1 increases. The weekly time series of cases will be our data for I at each time-step. Given the serial interval of measles is roughly two weeks, we will aggregate cases into two-weekly time steps.

# Function to return negative log-likelihood of I given model parameters
llik.cb = function(S0, beta, I) {
  n = length(I)
  S = floor(S0 - cumsum(I[-n]))
  p = 1 - exp(-beta * (I[-n])/S0)
  L = -sum(dbinom(I[-1], S, p, log = TRUE))
  return(L)
}

# Candidate values for S_0 and beta
S0cand=6500
betacand=seq(0,10, by=.1)

# Aggregate cases in district 1 into two-weekly time steps
twoweek = rep(1:15, each = 2)
y = sapply(split(niamey$cases_1[1:30], twoweek), sum)

# Implement model and record outputs of negative log-likelihood
# We derive the beta candidate value that yields the lowest negative log-likelihood
ll=rep(NA, length(betacand))
for(i in 1:length(betacand)){
ll[i]=llik.cb(S0=S0cand, beta=betacand[i], I=y)
}
betacand[which.min(ll)]
## [1] 2.3
par(mar = c(5,5,2,5))
p.beta <- plot(ll~betacand, ylab="Negative log-likelihood", xlab=expression(beta))

We thus estimate that, assuming S_0 = 6,500, the most plaussible value for is of 2.3. Similarly, we can cross-check this proposed valua against a plaussible range for S_0.

betacand=2.3
S0cand=seq(5920,8000, length=101)
ll=rep(NA, length=101)
for(i in 1:101){
  ll[i]=llik.cb(S0=S0cand[i], beta=betacand, I=y)
}
S0cand[which.min(ll)]
## [1] 7084.8
par(mar = c(5,5,2,5))
plot(ll~S0cand, ylab="Neg log-lik", xlab=expression(S[0]))

Maximum likelihood for parameter estimation in a chain-binomial model

The value obtained for S_0 (7,084.8) then tells us our guess is good, but imperfect. Using the mle2 function from the bbmle package, both parameters can be varied at the same time for an estimate obtained by maximum likelihood. Whilst this method still yields imperfect results, it highlights our uncertainty given parameter interdependencies. Moreover, our uncertainty in parameter values can be quantified as a variance-covariance matrix.

fit=mle2(llik.cb, start=list(S0=7085, beta=2.3),
         method="Nelder-Mead",data = list(I = y))
summary(fit)
## Maximum likelihood estimation

cov2cor(vcov(fit))
##              S0       beta
## S0    1.0000000 -0.7444261
## beta -0.7444261  1.0000000

Note the strong negative correlation between parameters here. For example, similar epidemic trajectories can arise from having a large number of initial susceptibles and a low transmission rate, or a more moderate number of susceptibles and a higher transmission rate.

Stochastic simulation

Building on the statistical part of the chain-binomial model, we can write a stochastic function for simulating dynamics given estimated parameters. Here, 100 simulations are superimposed on the observed epidemic and we can observe our model gives a reasonable approximation of the underlying dynamics, as the observed epidemic is wrapped around the model iterations.

par(mar = c(5,5,2,5))

sim.cb=function(S0, beta, I0){
  I=I0
  S=S0
  i=1
  while(!any(I==0)){
    i=i+1
    I[i]=rbinom(1, size=S[i-1], prob=1-
                  exp(-beta*I[i-1]/S0))
    S[i]=S[i-1]-I[i]
  }
  out=data.frame(S=S, I=I)
  return(out)
}

plot(y, type="n", xlim=c(1,18),
     ylab="Cases", xlab="Bi-weekly cases")
legend("topleft", legend=c("Data", "Model"),lty=c(1,1), 
       pch=c(1,NA), col=c("red", "grey"))

for(i in 1:100){
  sim=sim.cb(S0=floor(coef(fit)["S0"]),
             beta=coef(fit)["beta"], I0=11)
  lines(sim$I, col=grey(.5))
}
points(y, type="b", col=2)
